  <p>Bermuda's history spans over 500 years, with various periods shaping the island into what it is today.</p>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Early History</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Discovery:</strong> Bermuda was first documented by European explorer <em>Juan de BermÃºdez</em> in 1503, although there's limited information about this visit.</li>
      <li><strong>Shipwreck:</strong> In 1609, the English ship <em>Sea Venture</em>, en route to Jamestown, Virginia, was shipwrecked on Bermuda's reefs, marking the beginning of English settlement.</li>
      <li><strong>Permanent Settlement:</strong> The first permanent English settlement was established in 1612, with St. George's as the capital.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Colonial Era</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Virginia Company:</strong> Bermuda was initially administered by the Virginia Company, then the Somers Isles Company from 1615 to 1684.</li>
      <li><strong>British Colony:</strong> In 1684, Bermuda became a British Crown Colony, with a governor and council appointed by the British monarch.</li>
      <li><strong>Slavery:</strong> Slavery was introduced in the 1620s, with enslaved Africans and Native Americans brought to the island.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>18th and 19th Centuries</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>American Revolution:</strong> During the American Revolution, Bermuda remained loyal to the British Crown and served as a base for British naval operations.</li>
      <li><strong>War of 1812:</strong> Bermuda played a significant role in the War of 1812, with British forces launching attacks on Washington, D.C., and Baltimore from the island.</li>
      <li><strong>Abolition of Slavery:</strong> Slavery was abolished in Bermuda and the rest of the British Empire in 1834.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>20th Century</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>World War II:</strong> Bermuda played a strategic role in World War II, with the United States establishing military bases on the island.</li>
      <li><strong>Independence Movement:</strong> In the 1960s and 1970s, Bermuda moved towards self-government, with a new constitution adopted in 1968.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Modern Bermuda</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>British Overseas Territory:</strong> Bermuda is a British Overseas Territory, with a premier and a parliament responsible for internal affairs.</li>
      <li><strong>Financial Services:</strong> Bermuda has developed a significant financial services sector, with many international companies incorporated on the island.</li>
      <li><strong>Tourism:</strong> Tourism is also a major industry, with visitors drawn to Bermuda's beaches, history, and culture.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

